\begin_layout Itemize
Market timing is higher level decision about asset allocation.
 Most investors, especially old time value investors almost religiously
 will tell you that they are not market timers.
 True is, that we all are market timers.
 At least at some point in time in investing, we time markets.
 We do it implicitly sometimes by holding back cash or explicitly by actually
 time the markets.
 But market timing is built into every investor's gene.
 Here is the reason - if you can time the market, a payoff is immense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The problem with market timing, except taxes and transaction costs, is the
 you can be out at the wrong time - in the process of switching from stocks
 to cash and back, you may miss the best years of the market.
 In 1975, Bill Sharpe suggested in his article on market timing, that unless
 you can tell a good year from a bad year 7 times out of 10, you should
 not try market timing.
 So you have to be right at least 70-80% of the time to break even from
 market timing.
 This was confirmed by Monte Carlo simulations on the Canadian market.
\end_layout

