 assumptions; paying higher prices to do it; and/or lowering the standards
 that have to be met if one is to do it.
 All of these things tend to entail the assumption of greater risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The combination of positive psychology and the increase in activity causes
 asset prices to rise, which encourages still more activity, further price
 increases, and greater risk-bearing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inevitably this virtuous circle takes on the appearance of being unstoppable,
 and this appearance causes asset prices and the level of activity to go
 too far to be sustained.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When the news eventually turns less positive and the environment becomes
 less hospitable, the levels of psychology, activity and risk-bearing prove
 to have been excessive, and the same goes for asset prices.
 The resulting price correction causes psychology to become less positive,
 which causes disinvestment, which puts further downward pressure on prices,
 and so forth.
 These are all elements that most financial cycles have in common, and that
 includes the cycle in real estate.
 But the real estate cycle incorporates another ingredient that the others
 generally don't share: the long lead times required for real estate development
 to take place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There can be significant delays.
 Before a new building can come to market, adding to the supply of space,
 economic feasibility studies and environmental impact studies have to be
 performed; a site has to be found and purchased; the building has to be
 designed; construction must be completed, etc..this process can run for several
 years, and in the case of a major project it can exceed a decade.
 But market conditions can change very significantly in the interim.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
There have always been ideas, stocks and IPOs that produced great profits.
 Yet the pressure to participate wasn't as great as it is today, because
 in the past the winners made millions, not billions, and it took years,
 not months.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In bubble territory: the fact that investors are willing to swallow a promise
 of return without risk is an infallible indicator that skepticism is in
 short supply, psychology is overheated, and the subject asset is overestimated
 and thus probably overpriced.
 Watch out for it, and resist if you can.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When the market is high in its cycle, they should emphasize limiting the
 potential for losing money, and when the market is low in its cycle, they
 should emphasize reducing the risk of missing opportunity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A few more things about the nature of cycles:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Cycles are inevitable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cycles' clout is heightened by the inability of investors to remember the
 past.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cycles are self-correcting, and their reversal is not necessarily dependent
 on exogenous events (events occurring in other areas).
 Trends create the reasons for their own reversal.
 Success carries within itself the seeds of failure, and failure the seeds
 of success.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cycles are often viewed as less symmetrical than they are.
 Boom/bust is a good illustration of cycle symmetry.
 Busts follow booms.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An effort to explain life through the recognition of patterns - and thus
 to come up with winning formulas - is complicated, in large part, because
 we live in a world that is beset by randomness and in which people don't
 behave the same from one instance to the next, even when they intend to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Economic cycle = business cycle (term mostly used in the past though).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One of the main determinants of each year's economic output is the number
 of hours worked.
 In turn, the most fundamental factor underlying increases in hours worked
 is population growth.
 Growth in the population means there are more people working each year
 to make and sell products (and also more people to buy and consume them,
 encouraging production).
 More production equals more GDP.
 If the population is growing, hours worked tend to grow, and so does GDP.
 Thus births are one of the main reasons for the usual presumption that
 economic growth will be positive.
 On the other hand, if the population is shrinking, positive GDP growth
 faces a significant headwind.
 Changes in birth rates generally take place over long periods of time,
 and when they do, they require years to affect GDP growth.
 So year-to-year changes in GDP are unlikely to be attributed significantly
 to changes in the birth rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GDP, in the long run, influences: demographic movements, determinants of
 inputs (such as unemployment rate or # of hours worked by each person),
 aspiration (profit motive and desire to live better for producing more),
 education, technology, automation, and globalization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Summary of economic cycles:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The output of an economy is economy is the product of hours worked and output
 per hour; thus the long-term growth of an economy is determined primarily
 by fundamental factors like birth rate and the rate of gain in productivity
 (but also by other changes in society and environment).
 These factors usually change relatively little from year to year, and only
 gradually from decade to decade.
 Thus the average rate of growth is rather steady over long periods of time.
 Only in the longest of time frames does the secular growth rate of an economy
 significantly speed up or slow down.
 But it does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Long-term economic growth is steady for long periods of time but subject
 to change pursuant to long-term cycles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Short-term economic growth follows the long-term trend on average, but it
 oscillates around that trend line from year to year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
People try hard to predict annual variation as a source of potential investing
 profit.
 And on average they're close to the truth most of the time.
 But few people do it right consistently; few do it that much better than
 everyone else; and few correctly predict the major deviations from trend.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Extreme economic cyclicality is considered undesirable.
 Too much strength can kindle inflation and take the economy so high that
 a recession becomes inevitable.
 Too much weakness, on the other hand, can cause companies' profits to fall
 and can cost people their jobs.
 Thus it is part of the job of central bankers and Treasury officials to
 manage cycles.
 Since cycles produce ups and downs that can be excessive, the tools for
 dealing with them are counter-cyclical and applied with a cycle of their
 own - ideally inverse to the economic cycle itself.
 However, like everything else involving cycles, managing them is far from
 easy.
 If it weren't, we wouldn't see the extremes we do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Early on, many central banks issued currency.
 Their primary roles may have been to issue currency and exchange it on
 request for gold or silver.
 Today, central banks are primarily concerned with managing economic cycles,
 with inflation - not to eliminate it, but to control it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The reasons for inflation are somewhat mysterious and unreliable and sporadic.
 Sometimes a given set of circumstances will give rise to inflation, and
 at other times the same circumstances will lead to more or less inflation,
 or to none at all.
 But in general, inflation is viewed as a result of a strong upward movement
 of the economic cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When the demand for goods increases relative to the supply, there can be
 "demand-pull" inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When inputs to production such as labor and raw materials increase in price,
 there can be "cost-push" inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, when the value of an importing country's currency declines relative
 to that of an exporting country, the cost of the exporter's goods can rise
 in the importing country.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost of goods can escalate for any of these reasons.
 That's inflation.
 But sometimes these events can occur without an accompanying acceleration
 of inflation.
 And sometimes inflation can increase without these things being present.
 There is a large psychological component that influences all of this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Central Banks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Central banks can try to influence inflation by reducing the money supply,
 raising interest rates and selling securities.
 When the private sector purchases securities from the central bank, money
 is taken out of circulation; this tends to reduce the demand for goods
 and thus discourages inflation.
 They can accomplish the goal of keeping inflation under control, but they
 also restrain the growth of the economy, with effects that can be less
 than beneficial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Most central bankers have two jobs: to limit inflation, which requires restraini
ng the growth of the economy, and to support employment, which calls for
 stimulating economic growth.
 In other words, their dual responsibilities are in opposition to each other,
 and thus their job requires a delicate balancing act.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An economic upswing tends to encourage employment but can cause inflation
 to accelerate.
 Stagflation or contraction, on the other hand, discourages inflation but
 can cut into employment.
 So the job of the central banker is to behave appropriately counter-cyclically:
 that is, to limit the extend of cycles, slowing the economy in times of
 prosperity in order to keep inflation under control, and stimulating the
 economy during slowdowns to support employment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Government
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Governments have a greater variety of responsibilities than central bankers,
 only a small portion of which are related to economic matters.
 They also are charged with stimulating the economy when appropriate, but
 not directly with controlling inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Governments' main tools for managing the economic cycle are fiscal, defined
 as being concerned primarily with taxing and spending.
 Cutting taxes, increasing government spending, and even distributing stimulus
 checks, making more money available for spending and investment.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The process that determines a company's profits is complex and multivariate.
 The economic cycle has a profound effect on some companies' sales but less
 on others.
 Largely because of differences in operating and financial leverage, a given
 percentage change in sales has a much greater impact on profits for some
 companies than for others.
 Companies' profits are much more volatile than GDP.
 More GDP means more consumption, and thus stronger demand for goods.
 That, in turn, means greater volumes sold and higher selling prices, more
 work and higher wages, and thus still more consumption.
 All those things together mean increased revenues for businesses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By definition, the collective sales of all businesses are one and the same
 as GDP, and they reflect the same rate of change.
 But that doesn't mean all companies follow the same pattern.
 It depends on a given industry.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Sales of industrial raw materials and components are directly responsive
 to the economic cycle.
 When business collectively increases its output - that is, when GDP expands
 - it takes more chemicals, metals, plastic, energy, wire and semiconductors
 to do so, and vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Everyday necessities like food, beverages and medicine aren't highly responsive
 to the economic cycle.
 People generally consume them regardless of what's going on in the economy.
 But demand isn't absolutely constant: people trade down in recessions -
 buying cheaper food and eating at home rather than in restaurants - and
 they trade up in times of prosperity.
 And, sadly, people who are struggling financially may cut down even on
 their consumption of "necessities" when forced to choose between food,
 medications and rent payments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Purchases of big-ticket "durable goods" - things like cars and homes for
 individuals and trucks and factory equipment for businesses - are highly
 responsive to the economic cycle.
 They are durable so they last a long time, so replacement can be deferred
 in times of economic weakness.
 Also, because they cost a lot, they are hard to afford in bad times and
 easier to afford in good times.
 And businesses generally need more of them when business is god and less
 when it isn't.
 These things make the demand for durables highly responsible to the economic
 cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Demand for everyday services generally isn't volatile.
 If they are necessary and low-priced, demand won't be highly sensitive
 to changes in the economy.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The economic cycle has a profound effect on some companies' sales but less
 on others.
 Largely because of differences in operating and financial leverage, a given
 percentage change in sales has a much greater impact on profits for some
 companies than for others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The pendulum of investor psychology - pendulum swings are seen:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
between greed and fear,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
between optimism and pessimism,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
between risk tolerance and risk aversion,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
between credence and skepticism,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
between faith in value in the future and insistence of concrete value in
 the present, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
between urgency to buy and panic to sell.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The superior investor is mature, rational, analytical, objective, and unemotiona
l.
 Thus he performs a thorough analysis of investment fundamentals and the
 investment environment.
 He calculates the intrinsic value of each potential investment asset.
 And he buys when any discount of the price from the current intrinsic value,
 plus any potential increases in intrinsic value in the future, together
 suggest that buying at the current price is a good idea.
 In order to be able to do all the above, the superior investor strikes
 an appropriate balance between fear (which is shorthand for risk aversion,
 dislike for loss, and respect for uncertainty and randomness) and greed
 (a.k.a.
 aspiration, aggressiveness and acquisitiveness).
 All people feel emotions, but superior investor keeps those conflicting
 elements in balance.
 The presence of the two offsetting forces leads to responsible, wise, and
 even-keeled behavior.
 The superior investor resists psychological excesses and thus refuses to
 participate in extreme swings in psychological extremes.
 Emotional investors will need a great deal of self-awareness and self-restraint
 to become good investors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Investor psychology rarely gives equal weight to both favorable and unfavorable
 developments.
 Likewise, investors' interpretation of events is usually biased by their
 emotional reaction to whatever is going on at the moment.
 Few of the people involved actually are objective.
 Expecting widespread clinical observation during a market mania makes about
 as much sense as saying "everyone knows the market has gone too far." If
 many people recognized that it had gone too far, it wouldn't be there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk is uncertainty with regard to future developments, and the possibility
 of bad outcomes.
 And the current state of the environment is key in determining how we should
 behave with regard to risk at that point.
 Risk is high when investors feel risk is low.
 The greatest source of investment risk is the belief that there is no risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Superior investing doesn't come from buying high-quality assets, but from
 buying when the deal is good, the price is low, the potential return is
 substantial, and the risk is limited.
 These conditions are much more the case when the credit markets are in
 the less-euphoric, more stringent part of their cycle.
 The slammed-shut phase of the credit cycle probably does more to make bargains
 available than any other single factor.
\end_layout

