\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Anchoring bias
\emph default
 - tendency to rely too heavily on piece of past information when making
 decision.
 Especially when it comes to stock prices.
 It's hard to avoid, but past prices are irrelevant to future prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: The best is to check a stock independently and objectively.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Neglect a probability
\emph default
 - ignoring or underestimating probabilities in decision making.
 What is the most likely scenario for a company for going forward? In reality,
 there is the whole spectrum of possible future outcomes that could influence
 possible returns of a company and your investment returns.
 Some companies that are stable may have a smaller spectrum of possibilities.
 For example FANG may have a much wider range of potential outcomes.
 Sometimes people are underestimating a probability of so called Black svan
 events (TODO).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid:
\series default
 Being ignorant of risks doesn't make them go away.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Restraint bias
\emph default
 - it's very tempting to continue investing more in what we believe are
 our best investment opportunities.
 It can easily get out of hand if you're not conscious of it.
 On one hand, if you see and investment that you've made do really well,
 you might be tempted to put more money there, hoping that those gains will
 continue to raise further.
 However, there's also a possibility that one of your investment has fallen
 and thus provides the temptation to add more money to reduce your cost
 basis further.
 But it can lead to having a position too large for one's risk appetite
 within your portfolio.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: Before even buying a stock, you have to have an idea of the maximum mount
 of stock you want of that within your portfolio and be very careful not
 to exceed that limit.
 You can have too much of a "good thing".
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Bandwagon effect / groupthink
\emph default
 - If a large group of people do or think the same way as us.
 It can give us a false sense of security when we have many people around
 us on the same boat.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: Having an independent objective thinking and don't always go with the
 herd.
 Group thinking are one of the primary reasons why we see many financial
 speculative bubbles.
 Such as dot-com bubble in 2010 (TODO) or cryptocurrency mania in 2017.
