\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Hindsight bias 
\emph default
- Looking at the past events and consider them more predictable than they
 actually were.
 Such as "oh, I should have buy X" or "I should sell Y".
 You can see a lot of mainstream articles that show these off.
 Hindsight bias hurts investors because it prevents them from learning from
 the past investment mistakes!! In the worst case, it can lead investors
 thinking that every successful investment they made was because of their
 keen judgment even if it wasn't.
 And it can cause investors to chalk up losses simply because of volatility
 and unpredictable events.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: Have a written thesis or investment idea for each investment you consider
 taking.
 This would include why you think this investment is of a good value, some
 risks of the investment, and also expected return.
 You can have sense of exactly what you were thinking every time you made
 an investment decision.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Oversimplification
\emph default
 - investment is a very complex topic! There are situations that are simply
 too complex or uncertain to boil down within a few simple arguments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: Focus on investing within your circle of competence.
 These are companies or industries you know the best.
 Circle of competence - intersection between: what do you like? where do
 you earn money? where do you spend money? 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Incentive-caused bias 
\emph default
- this covers the rewards investment can have on human behavior and how
 they can often lead to poor long-term decisions.
 People say - if you want to find the truth, follow the money.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: When investing into businesses, see how management is compensated.
 Look for compensation plans that are not too heavily skewed towards options
 and incentivize a management for both achieving long-term results, but
 also avoiding downside risk.
 Having the right incentives in place ensure that management is working
 for you as the owner and shareholder.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Loss aversion/endowment effect 
\emph default
- this is for people that prefer avoiding losses over achieving the same
 amount of gain.
 This is closely related to endowment effect, which is where someone places
 a higher value on a good that they own, compared to the same good that
 they don't know.
 Both combined can lead to a very strong bias and poor investment decisions,
 when an investor refuses to sell an investment at a loss in hopes of trying
 to make that money back.
 You see this in form of rationalized comments like "it's not a loss until
 you sell".
 However, you are also paying a significant opportunity cost.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: Keep a limited number of stocks in your portfolio and not to exceed that
 limit.
 This limit will force you to invest only in what you believe at that time
 because these are your best investment options.
 This will force you to cut your losses with investments that you no longer
 think are a good investment decisions.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Information bias 
\emph default
- tendency to evaluate information even when it's useless when making a
 decision or understanding an issue.
 This is particularly prevalent today, when you have access to nearly unlimited
 amount of information.
 However, the quality of such information is questionable as well as the
 relevancy.
 Much of these came from other people's opinions.
 This includes also looking at daily stock prices in a sense daily stock
 price are simply the markets day to day opinion on the stock, and are really
 not that relevant for making long-term decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
How to avoid
\series default
: Majority of investors would be perfectly fine only looking at their stocks
 once a week or even just once a month.
 Rarely there is an opportunity you would miss by not keeping up to day
 with a market.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Confirmation bias -
\emph default
 when an investor seeks out or emphasizes information that confirms an existing
 conclusion or belief that we have.
 This is probably the number one cause of investor mistakes, because investors
 will get overconfident when they keep seeing information that confirms
 the beliefs that they already have.
 This is a particularly difficult bias to fight against, because we naturally
 seek out information that we want to hear and avoid or reject information
 that goes against our current beliefs.
 Unfortunately, media and social networks supports cognitive bias.
 They promote information you want to hear.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
